## Bug
**Target**
K64F

**Toolchain:**
GCC_ARM

**Toolchain version:**
6.2.1 20161205 (I think)

**mbed-cli version:** 
1.0.0

**meed-os sha:** (I tried several different versions from the 5.2 and 5.3 branches, with similar results
[Mbed_socket_attach_test.txt](https://github.com/ARMmbed/mbed-os/files/819467/Mbed_socket_attach_test.txt)
)
bcf7085 Merge pull request #3755 from ARMmbed/release-candidate

**Expected behavior**
Here is the basic scenario:
1.      Create Ethernet interface and connect it.
2.      Create new TCP socket
3.      Connect socket to www.arm.com at port 80
4.      Sent basic http request ("GET / HTTP/1.0\r\n\r\n") 
5.      Sleep for 20 seconds (osDelay)
6.      Call recv to receive 10 bytes of data.
During the sleep period we don’t see any callbacks (we have verified that the server response does indeed arrive during that time and recv still not block even if the sleep is for 3 seconds).

My expectation is when attaching a callback function to a socket is there when data arrives for this socket the callback function will be called asynchronously.
In my testing I have discovered that the callback for incoming data comes only after the recv function is called and will not arrive if the function is not called(tested on both blocking and non-blocking TCP sockets). 
Note: Kevin bracey suggested in a discussion with him regarding this issue that we may need to call recv once before the data arrives to get a callback (so this was added to the example, but behavior is similar).
Also Note:the code in quesiton uses the Ethernet interface (LWIP?), our port directly over Lwip code, does return a callback in this case.
Also Note:  kevin also suggested that Pull request 3619 might resolve the issue, however I tried merging these changes locally and still found the same behavior.  

**Actual behavior**
no callbacks prior to calling the recv function after the send. this doesn't allow us to use the callbacks as a way to detect that data has arrived (if we have to call recv to get it, there is not much point in a callback)

**Steps to reproduce**
I checked using the following simplified function:

```c++
void socketAttachSanity()
{
	printf ("start socket sanity");
	const char* message = "GET / HTTP/1.0\r\n\r\n";
	char buffer[100] = { 0 };
	nsapi_error_t status = 0;
	
	SocketAddress translatedAddress; 
	TCPSocket* socketObj = NULL;
	
	EthernetInterface* netInterface = new EthernetInterface();
	if (NULL != netInterface)
	{
		printf("new interface created\r\n");
		status  = netInterface->connect();
		if (NSAPI_ERROR_OK == status)
		{
			printf("interface connected : OK \r\n");
		}
		else {
			printf(" \r\nfailed to connect interface\r\n");
			return;
		}
	}
	else 
	{
		printf(" \r\nfailed to allocate interface\r\n");
		return;
	}
	
	printf("interface connected : OK \r\n");
	socketObj = new TCPSocket(netInterface);
	if (socketObj == NULL)
	{
		printf(" \r\nfailed to allocate socket\r\n");
		return;
	}
	socketObj->set_blocking(false); // also works for false
	socketObj->attach(socketCallback1);
	
	status =  socketObj->recv(buffer, 0); // also works if reading a positive size
	
	printf ("recv with status: %d ", status );
	
	status = socketObj->connect("www.arm.com", 80);
		
	if (status != NSAPI_ERROR_OK)
	{
		printf(" \r\nfailed to allocate socket\r\n");
		return;
	}
	status = socketObj->send(message,strlen(message) );
	printf ("send with status: %d ", status );
	if (status < NSAPI_ERROR_OK)
	{
		printf(" \r\nfailed to send socket\r\n");
		return;
	}
		
	printf ("\r\nsleeeep\r\n" );
	osDelay(20000); // also works for busy wait instead of sleep
	printf ("\r\after sleep\r\n" );
	
	status =  socketObj->recv(buffer, 10);
	printf ("recv with status: %d ", status );
	if (status < NSAPI_ERROR_OK)
	{
		printf(" \r\nfailed to recv socket\r\n");
		return;
	}
		
	//cleanup
	socketObj->close();
	delete socketObj;
	netInterface->disconnect();
	delete netInterface;
	printf ("end socket sanity ");
}
```

